\u30e9\u30e9\u30e9.details: SFX for skipping and humming a happy tune.

\u30e9\u30d6\u30e9\u30d6.details: SFX that literally derives from the Japanese pronunciation of "love-love" as "rah-bu rah-bu."

\u30e9\u30af\u30e9\u30af.details: SFX derived from the adjective "easy" or 「楽な」.

\u30e9\u30f3\u30c3.details: SFX for sudden attention in one's gaze, like snapping to attention dramatically (can be used for comedic effect)

\u30e9\u30f3\u30e9\u30f3.details: SFX for skipping and humming a happy tune.
SFX for an eye expression, for intense, fiery eyes.

\u30e9\u30e9\u30ea.details: SFX for a light tinkling, ringing, bell-like, chime-like sound. Can be mechanical or digital, like from a video game.

\u30ef\u30c3.details: SFX for a cheer, or a happy atmosphere.

\u30ef\u30fc.details: (A crowd's) excited roar. See also *wai wai* and *wara wara*
SFX for cheering or SFX for cry of dismay or despair.

\u30ef\u30fc\u30a4.details: Positive cheering, expression of cheerfulness or happiness.

\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3\u30c3.details: SFX for a long, wailing cry of despair
SFX for a loud cry of outrage or unhappiness with something

\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3.details: SFX for crying loudly and hysterically.

\u30ef\u30fc\u30ef\u30fc.details: (A crowd's) excited roar. See also *wai wai* and *wara wara*
SFX for background noise of pedestrians on the street.

\u30ef\u30a2.details: Like the war cries of soldiers in battle, or cry of protest.

\u30ef\u30d5.details: SFX for dog "woof-ing", see also *Wafu wafu*.

\u30ef\u30d5\u30fc\u30f3.details: High-pitched, sad whine of a dog.

\u30ef\u30cf\u30cf.details: Full-on, loud laughter. See also *hahaha* (ハハハ).

\u30ef\u30a4.details: Feminine exclamation of delight, spoken by a character.

\u30ef\u30a4\u30ef\u30a4.details: To explain lively action/noise, like *Gaya gaya*

\u30ef\u30af\u30ef\u30af.details: Happy, cute anticipation. See also *baku baku*.

\u30ef\u30f3\uff01.details: SFX for the call of a dog or wolf.

\u30ef\u30f3\u30ef\u30f3.details: SFX for the sound of a dog calling.

\u30ef\u30ca\u30ef\u30ca.details: Trembling from fear or anger; trembling all over.

\u30ef\u30e9\u30ef\u30e9.details: Crowded people, usually small kids. See also *waa* and *wai wai*.

\u30ef\u30c3\u30b7.details: SFX for the sound one makes while motivating oneself to use physical effort or to exert oneself physically. Ex: Counting out "one-two-three, and a one-two-three" while doing jumping jacks.

\u30ef\u30bf\u30ef\u30bf.details: SFX for arms flailing around, trying to cover a mistake.

\u30ef\u30b6\u30ef\u30b6.details: To go through the trouble of doing something.

\u30f3\u30c3.details: As of surprise, effort, sleepiness, pain, or passion. Usually in context of exerting physical effort.

\u30f3\uff1f.details: Grunt, usually coming out in the form of a question.

\u30f3\u30dc\u30fc\u30c3.details: Kind of a slow reaction state, when one is very tired or groggy from lack of sleep or exhaustion. (Even the SFX is exhausted with the "n" sound before the *bo-* SFX.) See also *bo-*.

\u30f3\u30b4\u30fc\u30f3\u30ac\u30fc.details: SFX for unintelligible muttering or murmuring sounds, such as the sounds made when one is tossing and turning in one's sleep.

\u30f3\u30e2.details: SFX for eating with mouth closed.

\u30f3\u30f3.details: SFX for a grunt of effort, stress, or pain
Can be used as a question 「んん？」

\u30f3\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7.details: Sound made when exerting physical effort.
